# Trivy Ignore File
# Use this file to ignore false positives or accepted risks
# Copy to .trivyignore and customize for your project

# Format:
# CVE-ID [package-name] [exp:YYYY-MM-DD]

# Example: Ignore specific CVE
# CVE-2023-12345

# Example: Ignore CVE in specific package
# CVE-2023-12345 python-package

# Example: Ignore with expiration date
# CVE-2023-12345 exp:2024-12-31

# Example: Ignore CVE with comment
# CVE-2023-12345  # Not exploitable in our use case

# ============================================
# Accepted Risks
# ============================================
# Document why each CVE is ignored below

# CVE-YYYY-XXXXX
# Reason: [Explain why this is acceptable]
# Mitigation: [Describe any mitigations in place]
# Review Date: [When to review this decision]
# Approved By: [Who approved this risk]

# ============================================
# False Positives
# ============================================
# Document false positives below

# CVE-YYYY-XXXXX
# Reason: False positive - [explain why]
# Verified: [Date verified as false positive]

# ============================================
# Temporary Ignores
# ============================================
# Use expiration dates for temporary ignores

# CVE-YYYY-XXXXX exp:2024-12-31
# Reason: Waiting for upstream fix
# Tracking: [Link to issue/PR]
